benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/admin/cache/accounts/{accountId} - Invalidates Caches per account level

covered: DELETE Valid Deletion: TC01 demonstrates successful deletion for a valid accountId.
Non-Existent Resource: TC02 (non-existent accountId) and TC16 (no accounts in system) cover 404 for missing resources.
Invalid accountId format: TC03, TC12 (regression for invalid UUID patterns) and TC14/TC15 (security tests with malformed inputs) cover input validation.
Missing path parameter: TC04 ensures behavior when accountId is not provided in the path.
Authentication/Authorization: TC05 (no auth) and TC06 (expired/invalid token) cover 401 responses for auth failures.
Unsupported method: TC11 tests 405 for disallowed HTTP method (GET on a DELETE endpoint).
Dependant/system conditions: TC07 (degraded performance) and TC08 (cache service unavailable) cover resilience under external conditions.
Concurrency and performance: TC13 (concurrent deletes with performance requirement) and TC17 (transient network failure recovery) cover concurrency and recovery scenarios.
Regression/Backward compatibility: TC19 ensures no regression with previous endpoint usage.
Edge cases: TC10 (very large/maximum-length accountId) and TC18 (partial/populated DB edge cases) validate boundary and state variation scenarios.
Security checks: TC14 (SQL injection attempt) and TC15 (XSS attempt) test input sanitization on accountId.
gaps: Caching Behavior: No tests validating HTTP caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or caching behavior for DELETE responses.
Rate Limiting: No tests verifying how the endpoint behaves under rapid successive requests or throttling scenarios.
Pagination: Not applicable for a single resource delete, but guideline mentions pagination generally; not needed here, but no explicit note on multi-resource scenarios is provided.
Soft Deletes: No explicit check if deletion is soft (flagged) vs hard delete.
Detailed non-authenticated/forbidden separation: 401 vs 403 distinction not explicitly differentiated in tests (tests use 401 for auth failures).
Explicit 404 when attempting to delete with a valid accountId but system state misaligns (e.g., partially populated DB) beyond TC18; more granular edge cases could be added.
recommendations: Add tests for caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) to verify proper caching semantics on DELETE responses, if applicable.
Add rate-limiting/throttling tests to ensure the API gracefully handles bursts of DELETE requests without erroring inappropriately.
Clarify and test soft-delete behavior if the system uses soft deletion (e.g., a “deleted” flag) versus permanent removal.
Include a dedicated 403 scenario for authenticated-but-unauthorized users if the role-based access model is used (in addition to 401).
Consider additional edge cases with more complex/invalid UUID patterns and extreme edge lengths to strengthen input validation coverage.
